nodes.label: Geometric Construction
nodes.title: The process of drawing geometric figures using only specific tools such as a straight edge and compass, following precise steps.

nodes.label: Dynamic Geometry Software
nodes.title: Computer programs that allow users to construct and manipulate geometric figures dynamically to explore properties and relationships.

nodes.label: Circle Construction with Given Radius
nodes.title: Drawing a circle with a specified radius using a compass and other geometric tools.

nodes.label: Use of Geometric Instruments
nodes.title: The appropriate use of tools such as straight edge, compass, ruler, protractor, and set square for constructing and measuring geometric figures.

nodes.label: Application of Constructions in Real-Life Contexts
nodes.title: Using geometric construction techniques to solve practical problems or model real-world situations.

nodes.label: Cartesian plane
nodes.title: A two-dimensional plane defined by a horizontal axis (x-axis) and a vertical axis (y-axis), used for plotting points, lines, and curves.

nodes.label: Co-ordinating the plane
nodes.title: Assigning ordered pairs of numbers to points on the Cartesian plane to represent their positions.

nodes.label: Linear relationship
nodes.title: A relationship between two variables that can be represented by a straight line on a graph, typically expressed in the form y = mx + c.

nodes.label: Tabular representation of linear relationships
nodes.title: Displaying values of variables in a table to show how one variable changes in relation to another in a linear relationship.

nodes.label: Graphical representation of linear relationships
nodes.title: Plotting points and drawing straight lines on the Cartesian plane to represent linear relationships between variables.

nodes.label: Slope of a graph
nodes.title: A measure of the steepness of a line, representing the rate of change between two variables in a linear relationship.

nodes.label: Rate of change
nodes.title: The amount by which one variable changes in relation to another; in linear relationships, this is equivalent to the slope.

nodes.label: Start value (y-intercept)
nodes.title: The value of the dependent variable when the independent variable is zero; represented by the y-intercept in the equation of a line.

nodes.label: Point of intersection of two linear relationships
nodes.title: The point on the Cartesian plane where two lines cross, representing the solution to a system of two linear equations.

nodes.label: Comparing linear relationships
nodes.title: Analyzing and contrasting the properties (such as slope and y-intercept) of two or more linear relationships, often in real-life contexts.

nodes.label: Solving real-life problems using linear relationships
nodes.title: Applying strategies such as graphical, numeric, or mental methods to find solutions to practical problems involving up to two linear relationships.

nodes.label: Right-angled triangle
nodes.title: A triangle in which one of the angles is exactly 90 degrees.

nodes.label: Theorem of Pythagoras
nodes.title: A theorem stating that in a right-angled triangle, the square of the hypotenuse equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides.

nodes.label: Applying Pythagoras' theorem to solve problems
nodes.title: Using the Pythagorean theorem to find unknown side lengths in right-angled triangles, especially in real-world contexts involving heights and distances.

nodes.label: Trigonometric ratios
nodes.title: Ratios of the lengths of sides in a right-angled triangle, specifically sine, cosine, and tangent.

nodes.label: Using trigonometric ratios to solve real-world problems
nodes.title: Applying sine, cosine, and tangent to calculate unknown angles or side lengths in practical situations involving right-angled triangles.

nodes.label: Solving right-angled triangle problems involving heights and distances
nodes.title: Finding unknown heights or distances using properties of right-angled triangles and relevant mathematical tools.

nodes.label: translation
nodes.title: A geometric transformation that moves every point of a shape or object a constant distance in a specified direction.

nodes.label: central symmetry
nodes.title: A transformation where each point of a figure is mapped to another point directly opposite to a fixed center, at the same distance.

nodes.label: axial symmetry
nodes.title: A symmetry in which a figure is mapped onto itself by reflection across a line (axis of symmetry).

nodes.label: rotation
nodes.title: A transformation that turns a figure about a fixed point called the center of rotation, through a specified angle and direction.

nodes.label: enlargement
nodes.title: A transformation that produces an image that is the same shape as the original, but is a different size, using a center of enlargement and a scale factor.

nodes.label: center of enlargement
nodes.title: The fixed point in the plane about which all points are expanded or contracted during an enlargement.

nodes.label: scale factor (enlargement)
nodes.title: A number by which all distances from the center of enlargement are multiplied to produce the image; determines the size of the enlargement or reduction.

nodes.label: effect of enlargement on area
nodes.title: The area of a shape after enlargement is multiplied by the square of the scale factor.

nodes.label: axis of symmetry
nodes.title: A line that divides a shape into two parts that are mirror images of each other.

nodes.label: recognition of images under transformations
nodes.title: The ability to identify the result of applying a transformation (such as translation, rotation, symmetry, or enlargement) to a point or shape.

nodes.label: problem solving with enlargements
nodes.title: Applying knowledge of enlargements, including center and scale factor, to solve geometric problems.

nodes.label: synthetic geometry
nodes.title: A branch of geometry that relies on axioms, theorems, and logical reasoning rather than coordinates or algebraic methods.

nodes.label: geometric constructions
nodes.title: Procedures for creating geometric figures using only a compass and straightedge, such as bisecting angles or constructing perpendicular lines.

nodes.label: construction 16-21
nodes.title: Specific geometric constructions outlined in the referenced curriculum, typically involving compass and straightedge techniques.

nodes.label: construction 22
nodes.title: A particular geometric construction as specified in the curriculum, likely building on previous constructions.

nodes.label: theorem
nodes.title: A mathematical statement that has been proven to be true using logic and previously established statements.

nodes.label: proof
nodes.title: A logical argument demonstrating the truth of a mathematical statement.

nodes.label: axiom
nodes.title: A fundamental statement or assumption accepted without proof as a basis for reasoning.

nodes.label: corollary
nodes.title: A statement that follows readily from a previously proven theorem.

nodes.label: converse
nodes.title: A statement formed by reversing the hypothesis and conclusion of a given statement.

nodes.label: implies
nodes.title: A logical relationship where one statement being true guarantees the truth of another.

nodes.label: is equivalent to
nodes.title: A logical relationship where two statements are true under exactly the same conditions.

nodes.label: if and only if
nodes.title: A logical phrase indicating that two statements are both necessary and sufficient for each other.

nodes.label: proof by contradiction
nodes.title: A method of proving a statement by assuming the opposite is true and showing this leads to a contradiction.

nodes.label: theorems 7, 8, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18, 20, 21
nodes.title: Specific geometric theorems as outlined in the referenced curriculum, often foundational results in synthetic geometry.

nodes.label: corollary 6
nodes.title: A specific corollary derived from a previous theorem, as referenced in the curriculum.

nodes.label: ratios in geometry
nodes.title: The use of proportional relationships between segments or figures in geometric proofs and constructions.

nodes.label: Slope of a Line
nodes.title: A measure of the steepness or inclination of a line, typically represented as the ratio of the vertical change to the horizontal change between two points on the line.

nodes.label: Parallel Lines
nodes.title: Two lines in a plane that never intersect and have the same slope.

nodes.label: Perpendicular Lines
nodes.title: Two lines that intersect at a right angle (90 degrees), with slopes that are negative reciprocals of each other.

nodes.label: Linear Equation in Two Variables
nodes.title: An equation of the form ax + by + c = 0, representing a straight line in the Cartesian plane.

nodes.label: Area of a Triangle (Coordinate Geometry)
nodes.title: The calculation of the area of a triangle given the coordinates of its vertices, often using the determinant formula.

nodes.label: Equation of a Circle (Centre (h, k), Radius r)
nodes.title: The standard form (x-h)^2 + (y-k)^2 = r^2 representing all points (x, y) at a distance r from the centre (h, k).

nodes.label: Equation of a Circle (General Form)
nodes.title: The general equation x^2 + y^2 + 2gx + 2fy + c = 0, where the centre is (-g, -f) and the radius is sqrt(g^2 + f^2 – c).

nodes.label: Perpendicular Distance from a Point to a Line
nodes.title: The shortest distance from a given point to a specified straight line in the plane.

nodes.label: Angle Between Two Lines
nodes.title: The measure of the angle formed where two lines intersect, calculated using their slopes.

nodes.label: Internal Division of a Line Segment
nodes.title: Dividing a line segment into a given ratio m:n internally, finding the coordinates of the dividing point.

nodes.label: Intersection of a Line and a Circle
nodes.title: Solving problems involving the points where a straight line meets a circle, typically by solving simultaneous equations.

nodes.label: Pythagoras' Theorem in 2D
nodes.title: Using the Pythagorean theorem to solve problems involving right-angled triangles in two dimensions.

nodes.label: Area of a Triangle using Trigonometry
nodes.title: Calculating the area of a triangle using trigonometric relationships, such as 1/2 ab sin(C).

nodes.label: Sine Rule
nodes.title: A rule relating the sides and angles of any triangle: a/sinA = b/sinB = c/sinC.

nodes.label: Cosine Rule
nodes.title: A rule relating the lengths of sides of a triangle to the cosine of one of its angles: c^2 = a^2 + b^2 - 2ab cos(C).

nodes.label: Definition of sin(θ) and cos(θ) for all θ
nodes.title: Defining the sine and cosine functions for all real values of θ, including negative and angles greater than 360°.

nodes.label: Definition of tan(θ)
nodes.title: Defining the tangent function as the ratio of sine to cosine for all θ where cos(θ) ≠ 0.

nodes.label: Area of a Sector of a Circle
nodes.title: Calculating the area of a sector using the formula (1/2) r^2 θ (in radians).

nodes.label: Arc Length of a Circle
nodes.title: Calculating the length of an arc using the formula rθ (in radians).

nodes.label: Trigonometric Ratios in Surd Form
nodes.title: Expressing sine, cosine, and tangent values in exact surd (root) form rather than as decimals.

nodes.label: Trigonometry in 3D
nodes.title: Applying trigonometric methods to solve problems involving three-dimensional figures.

nodes.label: Graphing Sine, Cosine, and Tangent Functions
nodes.title: Plotting the graphs of the basic trigonometric functions over a range of θ values.

nodes.label: Graphing Transformed Trigonometric Functions
nodes.title: Graphing functions of the form f(θ) = a + b sin(cθ) and g(θ) = a + b cos(cθ) for real constants a, b, c.

nodes.label: Solving Trigonometric Equations
nodes.title: Finding all solutions to equations such as sin(nθ) = 0 and cos(nθ) = 1/2.

nodes.label: Radian Measure of Angles
nodes.title: Using radians as a unit for measuring angles instead of degrees.

nodes.label: Derivation of Trigonometric Formulae
nodes.title: Deriving standard trigonometric identities and formulae.

nodes.label: Application of Trigonometric Formulae
nodes.title: Applying a range of trigonometric identities and formulae to solve problems.

nodes.label: enlargement (transformation geometry)
nodes.title: A type of transformation that changes the size of a figure by a scale factor, relative to a fixed point called the centre of enlargement.

nodes.label: centre of enlargement
nodes.title: The fixed point in the plane from which distances are measured in an enlargement transformation.

nodes.label: solving problems involving enlargements
nodes.title: Applying knowledge of enlargement transformations, including centre and scale factor, to solve geometric problems.

nodes.label: rational scale factor
nodes.title: A scale factor k used in enlargement transformations where k is a rational number (k ∈ Q).

nodes.label: Natural numbers (N)
nodes.title: The set of counting numbers starting from 1, often denoted as N = {1, 2, 3, ...}.

nodes.label: Integers (Z)
nodes.title: The set of whole numbers including negative numbers, zero, and positive numbers.

nodes.label: Rational numbers (Q)
nodes.title: Numbers that can be expressed as a fraction of two integers, including finite and repeating decimals.

nodes.label: Fractions
nodes.title: A way to represent rational numbers as a ratio of two integers.

nodes.label: Decimals
nodes.title: A representation of numbers using a decimal point, including finite and repeating decimals.

nodes.label: Percentages
nodes.title: A way to express numbers as a fraction of 100.

nodes.label: Addition of natural numbers
nodes.title: Combining two or more natural numbers to find their total.

nodes.label: Subtraction of natural numbers
nodes.title: Finding the difference between two natural numbers.

nodes.label: Multiplication of natural numbers
nodes.title: Finding the product of two or more natural numbers.

nodes.label: Division of natural numbers
nodes.title: Splitting a natural number into equal parts.

nodes.label: Addition of integers
nodes.title: Combining positive and negative whole numbers, including zero.

nodes.label: Subtraction of integers
nodes.title: Finding the difference between two integers, including negative results.

nodes.label: Multiplication of integers
nodes.title: Finding the product of two integers, including rules for signs.

nodes.label: Division of integers
nodes.title: Dividing one integer by another, including negative numbers.

nodes.label: Addition of rational numbers
nodes.title: Combining two or more rational numbers, including fractions and decimals.

nodes.label: Subtraction of rational numbers
nodes.title: Finding the difference between two rational numbers.

nodes.label: Multiplication of rational numbers
nodes.title: Finding the product of two rational numbers.

nodes.label: Division of rational numbers
nodes.title: Dividing one rational number by another.

nodes.label: Properties of arithmetic operations
nodes.title: Commutative, associative, and distributive laws governing addition and multiplication.

nodes.label: Commutative law
nodes.title: The order of addition or multiplication does not affect the result.

nodes.label: Associative law
nodes.title: The grouping of numbers in addition or multiplication does not affect the result.

nodes.label: Distributive law
nodes.title: Multiplication distributes over addition or subtraction.

nodes.label: Order of operations
nodes.title: The sequence in which arithmetic operations are performed, including the use of brackets.

nodes.label: Number line representation
nodes.title: Using a number line to visualize and compare numbers and operations.

nodes.label: Decomposition (in arithmetic)
nodes.title: Breaking numbers into parts to simplify calculations, especially in addition and subtraction.

nodes.label: Skip counting
nodes.title: Counting forward or backward by numbers other than one, used for multiplication and division.

nodes.label: Array model for multiplication
nodes.title: Arranging objects in rows and columns to represent multiplication.

nodes.label: Inverse operations
nodes.title: Operations that reverse the effect of each other, such as addition and subtraction, or multiplication and division.

nodes.label: Contextual problem solving with numbers
nodes.title: Applying arithmetic operations to solve real-life problems involving numbers.

nodes.label: Interpreting negative numbers in context
nodes.title: Understanding negative numbers as representing quantities such as debts or temperatures below zero.

nodes.label: Solving problems with fractional amounts
nodes.title: Applying arithmetic operations to solve problems involving parts of a whole.

nodes.label: Irrational Numbers
nodes.title: Numbers that cannot be expressed as a ratio of two integers; their decimal expansions are non-repeating and non-terminating.

nodes.label: Distinction between Real Numbers and Rational Numbers (R ≠ Q)
nodes.title: Understanding that the set of real numbers includes both rational and irrational numbers, and that not all real numbers are rational.

nodes.label: Operations in Number Domains (N, Z, Q, R)
nodes.title: Performing addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division within the sets of natural numbers (N), integers (Z), rational numbers (Q), and real numbers (R).

nodes.label: Complex Numbers in Rectangular Form (a + ib)
nodes.title: Expressing complex numbers as a sum of a real part and an imaginary part.

nodes.label: Operations with Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Performing addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division on complex numbers in rectangular form.

nodes.label: Argand Diagram
nodes.title: A graphical representation of complex numbers on a plane with real and imaginary axes.

nodes.label: Modulus of a Complex Number
nodes.title: The distance of a complex number from the origin on the Argand diagram, calculated as sqrt(a^2 + b^2) for a + ib.

nodes.label: Complex Conjugate
nodes.title: Given a complex number a + ib, its conjugate is a - ib.

nodes.label: Decimals as Equivalent Fractions
nodes.title: Understanding decimals as special cases of fractions and connecting them to place value.

nodes.label: Factors and Multiples
nodes.title: Understanding and identifying factors and multiples of natural numbers.

nodes.label: Prime Numbers
nodes.title: Natural numbers greater than 1 that have no positive divisors other than 1 and themselves.

nodes.label: Prime Factorization
nodes.title: Expressing a number as a product of its prime factors.

nodes.label: Order of Operations (including brackets)
nodes.title: Applying the correct sequence of operations in arithmetic expressions, including the use of brackets.

nodes.label: Scientific Notation (a × 10ⁿ, 1 ≤ a < 10, n ∈ Z)
nodes.title: Expressing numbers in the form a × 10ⁿ, where a is a real number between 1 and 10 and n is an integer.

nodes.label: Arithmetic Operations in Scientific Notation
nodes.title: Performing addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division with numbers expressed in scientific notation.

nodes.label: Geometric Construction of √2 and √3
nodes.title: Using geometric methods to construct the square roots of 2 and 3.

nodes.label: Proof that √2 is Irrational
nodes.title: Demonstrating that the square root of 2 cannot be expressed as a ratio of two integers.

nodes.label: Conjugates of Sums and Products of Complex Numbers
nodes.title: Calculating the complex conjugate of the sum or product of two complex numbers.

nodes.label: Number Patterns and Formulae Verification
nodes.title: Identifying patterns in sequences and verifying related algebraic formulae.

nodes.label: Geometric Sequences and Series
nodes.title: Sequences and series where each term is found by multiplying the previous term by a constant ratio.

nodes.label: Proof by Mathematical Induction
nodes.title: A method of mathematical proof used to establish that a statement holds for all natural numbers.

nodes.label: Sum of First n Natural Numbers
nodes.title: The formula for the sum of the first n natural numbers: n(n+1)/2.

nodes.label: Sum of a Finite Geometric Series
nodes.title: The formula for the sum of a geometric series with a finite number of terms.

nodes.label: Inequalities Involving Factorials and Powers
nodes.title: Proving inequalities such as n! > 2ⁿ, 2ⁿ ≥ n² (n ≥ 4), and (1 + x)ⁿ ≥ 1 + nx (x > –1).

nodes.label: Factorization Results (e.g., 3 is a factor of 4ⁿ – 1)
nodes.title: Proving divisibility and factorization properties for specific algebraic expressions.

nodes.label: Limits of Sequences
nodes.title: Finding the value that a sequence approaches as the number of terms increases.

nodes.label: Rules for Sums, Products, Quotients of Limits
nodes.title: Applying the properties of limits to sums, products, and quotients of sequences.

nodes.label: Limit of a Geometric Sequence
nodes.title: Determining the limit of a geometric sequence as n approaches infinity.

nodes.label: Finite and Infinite Geometric Series Applications
nodes.title: Solving problems involving geometric series, including recurring decimals and financial calculations like mortgage repayments.

nodes.label: Sum to Infinity of a Geometric Series
nodes.title: Deriving and applying the formula for the sum to infinity of a geometric series by considering the limit of its partial sums.

nodes.label: equality as a relationship
nodes.title: Understanding that equality means two mathematical expressions have the same value.

nodes.label: analysing solution strategies
nodes.title: Evaluating and comparing different methods for solving mathematical problems.

nodes.label: calculating percentages
nodes.title: Finding a percentage of a quantity or expressing a number as a percentage.

nodes.label: equivalence of fractions, decimals and percentages
nodes.title: Recognizing and converting between fractions, decimals, and percentages to compare proportions.

nodes.label: comparing proportions
nodes.title: Using equivalent forms (fractions, decimals, percentages) to compare relative sizes.

nodes.label: factors
nodes.title: Numbers that divide exactly into another number.

nodes.label: multiples
nodes.title: Numbers that are the product of a given number and an integer.

nodes.label: relationship between ratio and proportion
nodes.title: Understanding how ratios relate to proportions and how to use them to compare quantities.

nodes.label: checking results by order of magnitude
nodes.title: Assessing whether an answer is reasonable by considering its size relative to the problem.

nodes.label: working a problem backwards
nodes.title: Verifying solutions by reversing the steps of a calculation.

nodes.label: rounding off results
nodes.title: Reducing the number of digits in a number while keeping its value close to the original.

nodes.label: estimation and approximation
nodes.title: Making reasonable guesses or simplified calculations to obtain close answers.

nodes.label: presenting numerical answers to specified accuracy
nodes.title: Expressing answers with the number of decimal places or significant figures required.

nodes.label: expressing numbers in standard form (scientific notation)
nodes.title: Writing non-zero positive rational numbers as a × 10ⁿ, where 1 ≤ a < 10 and n is an integer.

nodes.label: Square Numbers
nodes.title: Numbers that are the product of an integer multiplied by itself (e.g., 4 = 2 × 2).

nodes.label: Cube Numbers
nodes.title: Numbers that are the product of an integer multiplied by itself twice (e.g., 8 = 2 × 2 × 2).

nodes.label: Square Roots
nodes.title: A value that, when multiplied by itself, gives the original number (e.g., √9 = 3).

nodes.label: Reciprocals
nodes.title: The reciprocal of a number is 1 divided by that number (e.g., reciprocal of 4 is 1/4).

nodes.label: Indices (Exponents)
nodes.title: A notation indicating how many times a number, the base, is multiplied by itself (e.g., a^n).

nodes.label: Contextual Problem Solving with Indices
nodes.title: Applying knowledge of indices, roots, and reciprocals to solve real-world or word problems.

nodes.label: Notation for Powers and Roots
nodes.title: Understanding and using mathematical notation such as a^2, a^3, √a to represent powers and roots.

nodes.label: Number sequences
nodes.title: An ordered list of numbers or objects generated by a specific process or rule.

nodes.label: Pattern recognition in sequences
nodes.title: Identifying regularities or repeated structures within a sequence of numbers or objects.

nodes.label: Extending sequences
nodes.title: Using identified patterns to predict and continue the sequence beyond the given terms.

nodes.label: Generalising patterns algebraically
nodes.title: Expressing the rule or relationship of a sequence using algebraic notation or formulas.

nodes.label: Arithmetic sequences
nodes.title: A sequence in which each term is found by adding a fixed number to the previous term.

nodes.label: Geometric sequences
nodes.title: A sequence in which each term is found by multiplying the previous term by a fixed number.

nodes.label: Classifying sequences
nodes.title: Determining whether a sequence is arithmetic, geometric, or neither based on its pattern.

nodes.label: Sum to n terms of an arithmetic series
nodes.title: Calculating the total of the first n terms in an arithmetic sequence using a specific formula.

nodes.label: Index notation
nodes.title: A mathematical notation for expressing repeated multiplication of the same number using exponents.

nodes.label: Product rule for indices
nodes.title: When multiplying powers with the same base, add the exponents: a^p × a^q = a^(p+q).

nodes.label: Quotient rule for indices
nodes.title: When dividing powers with the same base, subtract the exponents: a^p / a^q = a^(p−q).

nodes.label: Zero index rule
nodes.title: Any nonzero number raised to the power of zero is 1: a^0 = 1.

nodes.label: Power of a power rule
nodes.title: Raising a power to another power multiplies the exponents: (a^p)^q = a^(pq).

nodes.label: Negative index rule
nodes.title: A negative exponent represents the reciprocal: a^(−p) = 1/a^p.

nodes.label: Fractional indices
nodes.title: Exponents that are fractions represent roots: a^(1/q) = qth root of a.

nodes.label: Product of powers with different bases
nodes.title: Multiplying different bases with the same exponent: (ab)^p = a^p × b^p.

nodes.label: Quotient of powers with different bases
nodes.title: Dividing different bases with the same exponent: (a/b)^p = a^p / b^p.

nodes.label: Logarithm laws
nodes.title: Rules for manipulating logarithmic expressions, including product, quotient, and power rules.

nodes.label: Product rule for logarithms
nodes.title: The logarithm of a product is the sum of the logarithms: log_a(xy) = log_a x + log_a y.

nodes.label: Quotient rule for logarithms
nodes.title: The logarithm of a quotient is the difference of the logarithms: log_a(x/y) = log_a x − log_a y.

nodes.label: Power rule for logarithms
nodes.title: The logarithm of a power is the exponent times the logarithm: log_a(x^q) = q log_a x.

nodes.label: Logarithm of the base
nodes.title: The logarithm of a base to itself is 1: log_a a = 1.

nodes.label: Logarithm of one
nodes.title: The logarithm of 1 to any base is 0: log_a 1 = 0.

nodes.label: Change of base formula for logarithms
nodes.title: Allows conversion of logarithms from one base to another: log_a x = log_b x / log_b a.

nodes.label: Generalising patterns in algebraic form
nodes.title: Expressing the rule or relationship of a sequence using algebraic notation.

nodes.label: Index Laws
nodes.title: Rules governing the manipulation of expressions involving powers (indices), such as the product, quotient, and power of powers rules.

nodes.label: Product of Powers Rule
nodes.title: For the same base, multiplying powers adds the exponents: a^p * a^q = a^{p+q}.

nodes.label: Quotient of Powers Rule
nodes.title: For the same base, dividing powers subtracts the exponents: a^p / a^q = a^{p-q}.

nodes.label: Zero Exponent Rule
nodes.title: Any nonzero number raised to the power of zero equals one: a^0 = 1.

nodes.label: Negative Exponent Rule
nodes.title: A negative exponent indicates the reciprocal: a^{-p} = 1 / a^p.

nodes.label: Fractional Exponent Rule
nodes.title: A fractional exponent denotes roots: a^{1/q} = q-th root of a.

nodes.label: Power of a Product Rule
nodes.title: Raising a product to a power distributes the exponent: (ab)^p = a^p * b^p.

nodes.label: Power of a Quotient Rule
nodes.title: Raising a quotient to a power distributes the exponent: (a/b)^p = a^p / b^p.

nodes.label: Change of Base Formula
nodes.title: Allows logarithms to be converted between bases: log_a x = log_b x / log_b a.

nodes.title: Using index laws and logarithms to solve equations involving exponents.

nodes.label: Solving Logarithmic Equations
nodes.title: Using logarithmic laws and properties to solve equations involving logarithms.

nodes.label: surface area
nodes.title: The total area of all the surfaces of a three-dimensional object.

nodes.label: volume
nodes.title: The amount of space occupied by a three-dimensional object, measured in cubic units.

nodes.label: perimeter
nodes.title: The total length of the boundary of a two-dimensional figure.

nodes.label: area of a disc
nodes.title: The measure of the region enclosed by a circle, calculated as πr².

nodes.title: Approximating the area of shapes that do not have standard formulas by using strategies such as counting squares or decomposing into regular shapes.

nodes.label: volume of a rectangular solid
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a box-shaped object, calculated as length × width × height.

nodes.label: volume of a cylinder
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a cylinder, calculated as πr²h.

nodes.label: volume of a sphere
nodes.title: The amount of space inside a sphere, calculated as (4/3)πr³.

nodes.label: surface area of a rectangular solid
nodes.title: The total area of all six faces of a rectangular box, calculated as 2(lw + lh + wh).

nodes.label: surface area of a cylinder
nodes.title: The total area of the curved surface and the two bases of a cylinder, calculated as 2πrh + 2πr².

nodes.label: surface area of a sphere
nodes.title: The total area of the surface of a sphere, calculated as 4πr².

nodes.label: circumference of a circle
nodes.title: The distance around a circle, calculated as 2πr or πd.

nodes.label: relationship between circumference, diameter, and pi
nodes.title: Understanding that the circumference of a circle is equal to pi times the diameter (C = πd).

nodes.label: scaled diagrams
nodes.title: Drawings that represent objects with proportional dimensions, used to interpret and solve measurement problems.

nodes.label: modelling real-world situations with measurement
nodes.title: Applying concepts of length, area, and volume to solve practical, real-life problems.

nodes.label: Order of Magnitude Estimation
nodes.title: Checking whether a calculated result is reasonable by comparing it to an expected scale or size.

nodes.label: Reverse Calculation
nodes.title: Verifying a solution by working backwards from the answer to the original problem.

nodes.label: Rounding Off
nodes.title: Approximating a number to a specified degree of accuracy, such as to the nearest whole number or decimal place.

nodes.label: Error Accumulation in Addition and Subtraction
nodes.title: Understanding how small errors can combine when performing repeated addition or subtraction.

nodes.label: Estimation and Approximation of Calculations
nodes.title: Making and justifying rough calculations to simplify problem-solving.

nodes.label: Percentage Error
nodes.title: Calculating the relative error as a percentage of the true value.

nodes.label: Tolerance
nodes.title: The allowable deviation from a specified value, often expressed as a range.

nodes.label: Average Rate of Change
nodes.title: Calculating the change in a quantity divided by the change in time.

nodes.label: Cost Price Calculation
nodes.title: Determining the original price paid for goods before any profit or loss.

nodes.label: Loss Calculation
nodes.title: Finding the difference when the selling price is less than the cost price.

nodes.label: Mark Up (Profit as a Percentage of Cost Price)
nodes.title: Calculating profit as a percentage of the cost price.

nodes.label: Margin (Profit as a Percentage of Selling Price)
nodes.title: Calculating profit as a percentage of the selling price.

nodes.label: Compound Interest
nodes.title: Calculating interest on both the initial principal and the accumulated interest from previous periods.

nodes.label: Depreciation (Reducing Balance Method)
nodes.title: Calculating the decrease in value of an asset using a fixed percentage of the remaining value each period.

nodes.label: Income Tax Calculation
nodes.title: Determining the amount of tax owed based on income.

nodes.label: Net Pay Calculation (Including Deductions)
nodes.title: Calculating take-home pay after subtracting taxes and other deductions from gross income.

nodes.label: Costing: Materials, Labour, and Wastage
nodes.title: Calculating total costs by considering material, labor, and waste expenses.

nodes.label: Metric System Unit Conversion
nodes.title: Changing measurements between different metric units (e.g., meters to centimeters).

nodes.label: Imperial to Metric Unit Conversion
nodes.title: Converting measurements from imperial units (e.g., inches, pounds) to metric units using provided conversion factors.

nodes.label: Estimation of Physical Measures
nodes.title: Making reasonable guesses of measurements in real-world contexts.

nodes.label: Present Value Calculation
nodes.title: Determining the current worth of a sum of money to be received or paid in the future, used in loan repayments and investments.

nodes.label: nets of prisms
nodes.title: A net is a two-dimensional pattern that can be folded to form a three-dimensional prism.

nodes.label: nets of cylinders
nodes.title: A net for a cylinder consists of two circles and a rectangle that can be folded to form the surface of a cylinder.

nodes.label: nets of cones
nodes.title: A net for a cone consists of a sector of a circle and a circle, which can be folded to form the surface of a cone.

nodes.label: perimeter of plane figures
nodes.title: The total length around the boundary of a two-dimensional shape.

nodes.label: area of a parallelogram
nodes.title: The measure of the region enclosed by a parallelogram, calculated as base × height.

nodes.label: area of a trapezium
nodes.title: The measure of the region enclosed by a trapezium, calculated as 1/2 × (sum of parallel sides) × height.

nodes.label: area of sectors of discs
nodes.title: The measure of the region of a sector of a circle, calculated as (θ/360) × πr² for a sector with angle θ.

nodes.label: area of composite figures
nodes.title: Finding the area of a figure made up of a combination of basic shapes.

nodes.label: surface area of a rectangular block
nodes.title: The total area of all the faces of a rectangular prism.

nodes.label: surface area of a right cone
nodes.title: The total area of the curved surface and the base of a right circular cone.

nodes.label: surface area of a triangular-based prism
nodes.title: The total area of all faces of a prism with a triangular base.

nodes.label: surface area of a hemisphere
nodes.title: The total area of the curved surface and the base of a hemisphere.

nodes.label: surface area of composite solids
nodes.title: Finding the surface area of a solid made from combinations of basic solids.

nodes.label: volume of a rectangular block
nodes.title: The amount of space enclosed by a rectangular prism, calculated as length × width × height.

nodes.label: volume of a right cone
nodes.title: The amount of space enclosed by a right circular cone, calculated as (1/3)πr²h.

nodes.label: volume of a triangular-based prism
nodes.title: The amount of space enclosed by a prism with a triangular base, calculated as area of base × height.

nodes.label: volume of a hemisphere
nodes.title: The amount of space enclosed by a hemisphere, calculated as (2/3)πr³.

nodes.label: volume of composite solids
nodes.title: Finding the volume of a solid made from combinations of basic solids.

nodes.label: trapezoidal rule
nodes.title: A numerical method for approximating the area under a curve by dividing it into trapezoids.
